TEXT 48 -152 Left 4 ;Bootstrapped push-pull output stage
TEXT 816 368 Left 2 ;This is a bootstrapped push-pull output stage. \n \nCapacitor C1 feeds the output back to one end of R2, whose other end is driving the \nbase of Q2. This means that the voltage drop across R2 stays constant and \ntherefore it appears as a current source.\n \nThis makes Q1's load constant and able to drive the signal even at its peak.\n \nAt signal peak, due to the charge in C1, the voltage at point 1 is\nhigher than the signal peak - in this case, being R1 and R2 the same value, it will\nbe 1.5 the signal peak.\n \nC1 value must be chosen to have low impedance at signal frequencies compared to\nR1 and R2.\n \nAC Analysis\nPlot V(2)-V(1) to see that R2 acts as a current source.\n \nTransient analysis\nPlot V(1) to assess its value
